<br>
I don't know how accurate this is, but it has always been my impression that as mortals, we exist in linear time, and we know that Christ's passion and death happened at one point in time.  However, Jesus IS God, and God is a-temporal.  He, as the creator of time itself, is not bound by the restraints of what we perceive to be it's linear nature.  Now, we also know that Christ died for the sins of the world past, present and future.  For that to be the case, His suffering and death had to occur once, but be effective forever past and forever future.  In that regard, it could be said that His sacrifice exists at all points in time and the sacrifice at the Catholic Mass is simply that eternal nature of God, Jesus and his death for us.  We don't &quot;re-do&quot; it, as it simply IS.  Always.<br>
<br>
Wow, this is not easy to explain.<br>
<br>
I know this really isn't addressing the &quot;bloodless&quot; issue you encountered in the Eastern Orthodox service - but I could only respond from a Catholic perspective.<br>
<br>
Just as an FYI, here is a Liturgy of the Eucharist from a Catholic service.  Just as a comparison.<br>
